                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">3</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">When we are by providential occurrence<lb/> raised from poverty to\n                affluence to whom<lb/> can we communicate the delightful tidings<lb/> but our\n                friend? Au contraire, when we are<lb/> reduced from the highest pinnacle of<lb/>\n                grandeur to the most abject state of<lb/> deprivation, to whom can we look for\n                solid<lb/> consolation but <hi rend=\"underline\">God</hi>, and our friend?<lb/>\n                Indeed there is not a state or condition in<lb/> life where friendship is not\n                necessary.<lb/> What wretched mortals we would be<lb/> were it not for this noble\n                principle. <del>termed</del><lb/> Friendship is of a very delicate nature,<lb/> and\n                either the happiness or misery of<lb/> both parties, may in some sense be said<lb/>\n                to depend on it, it is made for life; or as<lb/>\n                <persName><sic>Cesar</sic></persName> said “The die is cast.” When I<lb/> contract a\n                friendship it is for eternity.<lb/> There is not an endearing attribute of<lb/> the\n                Deity; not an <sic>aimiable</sic> quality in<lb/> man, but what is included I\n                the<lb/> word Friendship. Benevolence,<lb/> mercy, pity, and compassion are</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3st7fd2s/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
